\nmultilingual BERT models in toxicity detection in text comments in their\npre-trained language.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Nov 2021 14:24:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-09"}
{"id":"2111.04531","submitter":"Gopal Hazra","authors":"Gopal Hazra, Aline A. Vidotto, Stephen Carolan, Carolina Villarreal\n  D'Angelo and Ward Manchester","title":"The impact of coronal mass ejections and flares on the atmosphere of the\n  hot Jupiter HD189733b","comments":"Accepted for publication in MNRAS, 14 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stab3271","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.SR physics.plasm-ph physics.space-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  High-energy stellar irradiation can photoevaporate planetary atmospheres,\nwhich can be observed in spectroscopic transits of hydrogen lines. For the\nexoplanet HD189733b, multiple observations in the Ly-$\\alpha$ line have shown\nthat atmospheric evaporation is variable, going from undetected to enhanced\nevaporation in a $1.5$-year interval. Coincidentally or not, when HD189733b was\nobserved to be evaporating, a stellar flare had just occurred 8h prior to the\nobservation. This led to the question of whether this temporal variation in\nevaporation occurred due to the flare, an unseen associated coronal mass\nejection (CME), or even the effect of both simultaneously. In this work, we\ninvestigate the impact of flares (radiation), winds, and CMEs (particles) on\nthe atmosphere of HD189733b using 3D radiation hydrodynamic simulations of\natmospheric evaporation that self-consistently include stellar photon heating.\nWe study four cases: first- the quiescent phase of the star including stellar\nwind, second- a flare, third- a CME, and fourth- a flare that is followed by a\nCME. Compared to the quiescent case, we find that the flare alone increases the\nevaporation rate by only 25%, while the CME leads to a factor of 4 increase in\nescape rate. We calculate Ly-$\\alpha$ synthetic transits and find that the\nflare alone cannot explain the observed high blueshifted velocities seen in the\nLy-$\\alpha$ observation. The CME, however, leads to an increase in the velocity\nof the escaping atmosphere, enhancing the transit depth at high blueshifted\nvelocities. While the effects of CMEs show a promising potential to explain the\nblueshifted line feature, our models are not able to fully explain the\nblueshifted transit depths, indicating that they might require additional\nphysical mechanisms.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Nov 2021 14:24:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-24"}
